# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hitachi-3tours-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/acn-championship] The **Diamond Cup Golf** (アジアパシフィックオープンゴルフチャンピオンシップ ダイヤモンドカップゴルフ, *Ajia pashifikku opun gorufu chanpionshippu Daiyamondo kappu gorufu*) is a professional golf tournament on the Japan Golf Tour.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/acn-championship] Founded in 1969, the event has been hosted at different courses throughout Japan, including on all four major islands.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/acn-championship] From 2014 to 2019 the tournament was co-sanctioned by the Asian Tour.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Miyazato was born on 19 June 1985 in Higashi, Okinawa, Japan.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Her father and brothers are professional golfers.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Her older brother Yūsaku has won seven times on the Japan Golf Tour and played in the 2018 Masters Tournament.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] As an amateur in 2003, she won a professional event on the LPGA of Japan Tour, the Dunlop Ladies Open, in Miyagi Prefecture where she was attending high school at the time.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] In her 2004 rookie season on the JLPGA Tour Miyazato won five tournaments.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] In February 2005, she represented Japan along with Rui Kitada and won the inaugural Women's World Cup of Golf.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] In 2005, she won six events on the JLPGA tour, and was the #2 ranked player on the JLPGA Tour behind Yuri Fudoh.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] In winning the Japan Open Championship at age 20 in 2005, Miyazato became the youngest player on the JLPGA Tour to win a major.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Furthering the notion that Miyazato revived the JLPGA Tour after the retirement of Ayako Okamoto, over 32,000 spectators, the largest gallery ever to attend a JLPGA event, witnessed the final round.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] At the LPGA Qualifying Tournament in Florida in December 2005, Miyazato easily secured her tour card for the 2006 season.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] She was under-par in four of the five rounds, and was 12 strokes ahead of the closest competitor, which set a record for the largest margin of victory.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Back in Japan, on 15 December, she played the opening rounds of the Okinawa Open, becoming the first Japanese woman to compete in a domestic men's professional event, although she failed to make the cut for the final rounds.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] In Miyazato’s fourth season on the LPGA Tour in 2009, she earned her first win at the Evian Masters in France, defeating Sophie Gustafson at the first hole of a sudden-death playoff.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] In 2010, Miyazato won four of the first nine official tournaments on the LPGA Tour and on 21 June rose to number 1 in the Women's World Golf Rankings.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] She held the spot for only one week and was replaced by Cristie Kerr who held the spot for three weeks, before Miyazato regained the spot again on 19 July, by a narrow margin of 0.0006 average points.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] In August, Miyazato won for the fifth time in 2010 at the Safeway Classic in Oregon, with a two-stroke victory over Kerr and Na Yeon Choi.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] She regained the top spot in the world rankings, which had been briefly retaken by Kerr, but then gave it up to Kerr on 25 October.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] In 2011, Miyazato won the Order of Merit on the Ladies European Tour (LET), despite only playing in two events on that tour, the co-sponsored events with the LPGA.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] The LET has no minimum tournament requirements for membership and her second win at the Evian Masters, whose purse is much larger than most LET events, earned her enough to top the list.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] In April 2012, Miyazato won her eighth LPGA event at the inaugural LPGA Lotte Championship in Hawaii, four strokes ahead of runners-up Azahara Muñoz and Meena Lee.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Miyazato has endorsements deals with Suntory, Bridgestone Corporation, Japan Airlines, Oakley, Honda, Hisamitsu, Mitsubishi Electric and NTT Docomo.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Her older brothers, Kiyoshi Miyazato and Yūsaku Miyazato are also professional golfers.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] She is not related to fellow Japanese LPGA Tour player Mika Miyazato.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] On 27 May 2017, Kyodo News Agency reported that Miyazato would retire at the end of the season.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Her last tournament was the 2017 Evian Championship.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Miyazato is the first golfer to have achieved the world number one ranking without ever winning a major.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] Position in Women's World Golf Rankings at the end of each calendar year.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] ^ Miyazato was last ranked on 25 September 2017.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-miyazato] She dropped from the ranking following her retirement.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-suzuki] Suzuki plays on the LPGA of Japan Tour where she has won 22 times including 7 times in 2019.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-suzuki] In November 2019, she won three consecutive tournaments, including the Toto Japan Classic, which was co-sanctioned by the LPGA Tour.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-suzuki] Suzuki led the LPGA of Japan Tour money list in 2017 and 2019.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ai-suzuki] Tournaments in **bold** denotes major tournaments in LPGA of Japan Tour.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/akie-iwai] Iwai was born in Saitama Prefecture and started playing golf at 8 years old.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/akie-iwai] In 2019, she won the Junior Golf World Cup.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/akie-iwai] Iwai turned professional and joined the LPGA of Japan Tour in 2021.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/akie-iwai] As a rookie she won a title on the developmental circuit, the Step-Up tour, and the JLPGA Rookies Championship.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/akie-iwai] She had her breakthrough in 2023 when she won three titles and finished second on the money list.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/akie-iwai] In 2024, she finished top-10 in two LPGA majors, and rose to 26th in the Women's World Golf Rankings.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/akie-iwai] In December 2024, Iwai earned her LPGA Tour card for 2025 by finishing T-5 at the LPGA Final Qualifying Tournament.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/akie-iwai] Her twin sister, Chisato, is also a professional golfer on the LPGA of Japan Tour.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ana-open] The **ANA Open** (ANAオープンゴルフトーナメント, *Ei-enu-ei ōpun golufu tōnamento*) is a professional golf tournament on the Japan Golf Tour.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ana-open] Founded as the **Sapporo Open**, it has been sponsored by All Nippon Airways since 1973, initially as the **ANA Sapporo Open**.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ana-open] It is usually held in September each year at the Sapporo Golf Club in Kitahiroshima, Hokkaido.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ana-open] Sapporo's Wattsu and Yuni courses have both played host to the tournament.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ana-open] The tournament scoring record is 268 (20 under par), set by Masashi Ozaki in 1994.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/ana-open] Ozaki also holds the all-time record of wins at the tournament with eight.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/hitachi-3tours-championship] The **Hitachi 3Tours Championship** (日立3ツアーズ選手権, *Hitachi surī tsuāzu sensyuken*) is an unofficial golf event held every December at the Glissando Golf Club Narita, Chiba, Japan.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/hitachi-3tours-championship] The tournament is a unique stroke play event, and, as the name suggests, pits teams from the Japan Golf Tour, the LPGA of Japan Tour, and PGA Senior Tour.
[src:hitachi-3tours-championship/hitachi-3tours-championship] The teams were made of five tour members from 2005 to 2009 and six members since 2010.
